Distance matrix¶

Correlation by itself is not a distance metric because:

  1. It can be negative
  2. Similar variables (high correlation) should be closer (small distance)

To transform correlation into a distance, we simply use 1 - abs(corr). The absolute solves problem 1 and subtracting from 1 solves problem 2

In [5]:
distance_matrix = 1 - corr.abs()
_ = sns.heatmap(distance_matrix, cmap="RdBu")

Ward clustering¶

In [9]:
# to store selected features
selected_features = []
In [10]:
def cluster_features_ward(dist_matrix, dist_threshold):
    dist_linkage = hierarchy.ward(distance.squareform(dist_matrix))
    cluster_ids = hierarchy.fcluster(dist_linkage, dist_threshold, criterion="distance")
    
    cluster_to_feature = collections.defaultdict(list)
    for feature_id, cluster_id in enumerate(cluster_ids):
        cluster_to_feature[cluster_id].append(dist_matrix.columns[feature_id])
    
    return cluster_to_feature

Cluster 3: profitability measures¶

In [14]:
def plot_cluster_corr_matrix(corr, cluster_map, cluster_id):
    cm = corr.loc[cluster_map[cluster_id], cluster_map[cluster_id]]
    sns.heatmap(cm, cmap="RdBu_r")
    print(f"Minimum absolute correlation: {cm.abs().min().min().round(2)}")

In [16]:
def compute_corr_with_target(df, cluster_map, cluster_id):
    return (
        df[clustering[cluster_id]]
        .corrwith(df["x00"], method="spearman")
        .round(2)
        .sort_values(key=lambda x: abs(x), ascending=False)
    )

The most important feature is x19: Persistent EPS in the last four seasons. The sign makes sense: the higher a company's earnings per share (EPS), the higher its profitability and thus the lower its bankruptcy risk. Lets calculate the skewness of those features to get an idea of how badly behaved are their distribution.

In [18]:
def compute_skew(df, cluster_map, cluster_id):
    return df[clustering[cluster_id]].skew().round(2).sort_values(key=lambda x: abs(x), ascending=False)

The most important growth measure here is x28: continuous net profit growth rate. It makes total sense: the more the net profit of a company grows, the less chance it has of going bankrupt. Yet growth measures are very ill-behaved, which also makes sense: some companies (like startups) have abnormally high growth rates compared to other companies. This leads to long tails in distribution. It will be harder to preprocess the chosen growth measure. I will chose x26: after-tax net profit growth rate. It is just slightly less predictive (it has about 92% of x28's correlation with the target), but much less asymmetric (it has only about 38% of x28's skewness), making the trade-off worthwhile. It also is a much more intuitive measure that should make interpretation of predictions easier.

Second round of Ward's clustering¶

Now that we narrowed the dimension down to 33 (of the original 96), it is time to further remove correlated features. Now, lets focus only on features if maximum absolute correlation above 40%. Every feature with maximum absolute correlation below 40% will be automatically selected.

In [113]:
CORR_CUTOFF = 0.4
temp = corr2.abs().max()
features = {x for x in temp[temp < CORR_CUTOFF].index}
